text: Barcode information can extracted raw fastq files summarised table counts per barcode follows Firstly define expected barcode pattern upstream downstream constant regions flank true barcodes. extract reads containing barcode pattern using extractbartoolseads function Following barcode extraction make use previously generated library reference barcodes map extracted sequences reference using mapbartoolseads. True barcodes align without mismatches. reads containing sequencing errors false barcode sequences snuck extraction step filtered . bowtie reference yet generated can specify reference_fasta place bowtie_index generated us mapBarcodeReads takes liberty counting number occurrences barcode us saving output file. can easily load examine final count data .
code: pattern <- "([ACTG][ACTG][GC][AT][GC][ACTG][ACTG][AT][GC][AT]){3,6}" fastq <- system.file("extdata", "test_extract_75bp_single-end.fastq.gz", package = "bartools", mustWork = T) constant <- toupper("tgaccatgtacgattgacta") test.extract <- bartools::extractbartoolseads(infile = fastq,                                barcode_pattern = pattern,                               constant = constant,                                yieldSize = 1e6) test.extract test.map <- bartools::mapbartoolseads(reads = test.extract,                                       bowtie_index = "../data/bowtie/index",                                       mismatches = 1,                                       threads = 1,                                       prefix = "test_map") test.map reference.fa <- system.file("extdata", "barcode_lib_reference_test.fasta", package = "bartools", mustWork = T) test.map <- bartools::mapBarcodeReads(reads = test.extract,                                       bowtie_index = NULL,                                       reference_fasta = reference.fa,                                       mismatches = 1,                                       threads = 2,                                       prefix = "test_map") test.map test.counts <- utils::read.delim("./test_map_counts.csv", header = T, sep = ",", row.names = 1) test.counts %>% tibble::rownames_to_column() %>% dplyr::arrange(dplyr::desc(mapped))
